avis traces the evolution of obsessive behavior from a social and religious fact of life into a medical and psychiatric problem. From obsessive aspects of professional specialization to obsessive compulsive disorder and nymphomania, no variety of obsession eludes Davis’s graceful analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCompulsive behaviorxHistory. 0aObsessive-compulsive disorderxHistory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aobsession, devotion, passion, commitment, infatuation, fervor, enthusiasm, affect, emotion, excess, addiction, obsessive compulsive disorder, compulsion, demonic possession, professional specialization, nymphomania, bibliomania, graphomania, monomania, fixation, freud, sex, love, visual art, psychiatry, medicine, nonfiction, history.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226137797423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226137797/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles